### Origin of the New Jersey settlement

The historical entity known as [Bergen](/Bergen_County,_New_Jersey) was, for a significant portion of the 17th century, an integral, if often embattled, component of the sprawling Dutch colonial province of [New Netherland](/New_Netherland). It occupied the strategic, resource-rich territory in what is now [northeastern New Jersey](/Gateway_Region), gracefully situated along the confluence and banks of the majestic [Hudson](/Hudson_River) and [Hackensack](/Hackensack_River) Rivers. This area would, in due course, evolve into the contemporary administrative divisions of [Hudson](/Hudson_County,_New_Jersey) and [Bergen](/Bergen_County,_New_Jersey) Counties, a testament to its enduring geographical and historical significance.

While its official recognition as an independent municipality didn't materialize until 1661, marked by the formal establishment of a village at what would become [Bergen Square](/Bergen_Square), the story of Bergen's origins stretches back further, a rather messy prologue of tentative European encroachment. Its nascent beginnings can be traced to a humble [factory](/Factory_(trading_post))—a trading post, not a place of industrial production, mind you—erected at [Communipaw](/Communipaw) around 1615. This initial, almost accidental, foothold was followed by the first concerted attempt at permanent settlement in 1630, taking the name [Pavonia](/Pavonia,_New_Netherland). These earliest, rather precarious, settlements were strategically positioned along the western banks of the [North River (Hudson River)](/North_River_(Hudson_River)), directly opposite the bustling, if still modest, hub of [New Amsterdam](/New_Amsterdam). Unsurprisingly, given their proximity and the nascent colonial power structure, they fell squarely under the administrative and judicial purview of [New Amsterdam](/New_Amsterdam) itself, hardly a picture of burgeoning independence.

A map from approximately 1634 offers a glimpse into this formative period, illustrating the nascent European presence. Intriguingly, early colloquial names for this region included "Oesters Eylandt," a rather literal nod to its extensive [oyster](/Oyster) beds, and "Achter Kol," a name whose etymology we will, unfortunately, have to delve into later. The three structures tentatively depicted on this map are generally understood to represent the embryonic settlements of [Communipaw](/Communipaw), [Paulus Hook](/Paulus_Hook), and [Harsimus](/Harsimus), each a tiny beacon of European ambition in a vast, untamed landscape.

